    <!-- 6. The story -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <h2 class="mb-4">📖 The story of AZERTY Global</h2>

        <div class="card mb-6">
          <p class="mb-4 text-secondary">
            In January 2016, the French Ministry of Culture published a damning report:
            <strong>it is impossible to type proper French on an AZERTY keyboard</strong>.
            No native accented capitals, no French quotation marks, no œ ligature...
          </p>
          <p class="mb-4 text-secondary">
            Following this report, AFNOR (the French standards body) was commissioned to create a new standard.
            In 2019, the <a href="https://norme-azerty.fr" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NF Z71-300 standard</a> was published. But this official solution
            imposes <strong>too abrupt a break</strong> with the Windows AZERTY,
            only partially addresses developers' needs, and <strong>has struggled to catch on</strong>:
            very few compatible keyboards are sold and adoption remains marginal.
          </p>
          <div class="page-presse__story-split mb-4">
            <p class="text-secondary">
              This is the context in which <strong>Antoine OLIVIER</strong>, then a student in a French
              preparatory class, decided to build his own solution. Passionate about ergonomic keyboards
              and keyboard layouts, he was fed up with the flaws of the traditional AZERTY.
              He has kept improving the project ever since.
            </p>
            <picture class="page-presse__story-media">
              <source srcset="/images/antoine-olivier-300.webp" type="image/webp">
              <img src="/images/antoine-olivier-300.png" alt="Antoine OLIVIER" width="150" height="150" loading="lazy" class="page-presse__story-photo">
            </picture>
          </div>
          <p class="mb-4 text-secondary">
            The goal: <strong>a layout based on the Windows AZERTY</strong> —
            to make the transition easy — while fixing its major flaws and adding
            many characters to type perfectly in French and in dozens of other languages.
            Since 2017, AZERTY Global has gone through several versions.
            <strong>The 2026 version is by far the most polished</strong>,
            the result of 9 years of research and continuous improvement.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="alert alert--info mb-6">
          <p class="alert__title">⚠️ Not to be confused with the AFNOR AZERTY</p>
          <p class="alert__text">
            AZERTY Global is an <strong>independent project</strong>, distinct from the <a href="https://norme-azerty.fr" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AFNOR standard (NF Z71-300, 2019)</a>.
            The two layouts share some goals but differ in their approach. AZERTY Global
            favors a <strong>smooth transition</strong> from the traditional Windows AZERTY.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="card__title">🏗️ The project's foundations</h3>
          <ul class="text-secondary pl-4 leading-loose">
            <li><strong><a href="https://www.dispoclavier.com/afnor/enq2017/comm/public/tout/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AFNOR public survey of June 2017 (in French)</a></strong> — Feedback from thousands of French people
              on the problems of the AZERTY keyboard guided the development priorities.</li>
            <li><strong>Study of foreign layouts</strong> — Inspiration from international best practices,
              such as dead keys on the number row (Hungarian layout) or the smart Caps Lock
              (Spanish QWERTY).</li>
            <li><strong>Intuition and daily practice</strong> — 9 years of daily use and continuous improvement of
              the layout by its creator.</li>
            <li><strong>Community feedback</strong> — Feedback from early users shaped the successive
              versions.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

